### B.1. S2 — Partial CPS coverage and regressive transfer up the distribution

The reconstructed CPS at [Appendix C.4](#c4-missing-cps-mapping-to-v2-3-1) has two sides: ROS convergence across pool sizes (delegator layer) **and** income support for the operators of small pools that cannot yet attract delegation (operator layer). CIP-0023 addresses the first and actively mis-allocates the second: a proportional margin floor of 1.5 % produces a per-pool operator-revenue change that scales with pool size, so the same mechanism meant to help the small-pool tier **redirects a far larger ADA amount to operators that already have no viability problem** — and the mis-allocation is amplified when the same operator runs many pools.

**Pool axis — Δ per pool across the nine canonical tiers** (epoch 623; reward $R(\sigma) \approx 24\,000 \times \sigma / 77\text{M}$ ₳/epoch below saturation; reward capped at saturation cap $z_0 = 77$ M ₳; convention "declared margin ≈ 0" as in the CIP's own worked example):

| Canonical tier | Rep. σ | $R_{\text{pool}}$ ₳/ep | Current op take | Standalone `minPoolMargin = 1.5 %` | **Δ per pool, std.** | Paired `minPoolCost = 50`, `minPoolMargin = 1.5 %` | **Δ per pool, paired** |
| --- | ---: | ---: | ---: | ---: | ---: | ---: | ---: |
| Dormant | 50 K | 15.6 | 15.6 | 15.6 | 0 | 15.6 | 0 |
| Sub-block | 500 K | 155.8 | 155.8 | 155.8 | 0 | 51.6 | **–104.2** |
| Sub-reliable | 2 M | 623 | 170 | 176.8 | **+6.8** | 58.6 | **–111.4** |
| Healthy | 15 M | 4 675 | 170 | 237.6 | +67.6 | 119.4 | –50.6 |
| Large healthy | 50 M | 15 584 | 170 | 401.2 | +231.2 | 283.0 | +113.0 |
| Near-saturation | 67 M | 20 883 | 170 | 480.7 | +310.7 | 362.5 | +192.5 |
| Saturated | 77 M | 24 000 | 170 | 527.5 | **+357.5** | 409.3 | **+239.3** |

*Table B.2 — Per-pool Δ in operator take across nine canonical tiers under the standalone and the (out-of-scope) paired variant.*

> **Finding CIP-0023.S2.F2 [R] — Per-pool Δ at Saturation is 52× the Δ at Sub-reliable.** +357.5 vs +6.8 ADA/epoch under the standalone variant — the instrument that the CIP's rationale introduces to *fund* small operators redirects the largest ADA transfer to pools that had no viability problem to begin with. The Dormant and Sub-block tiers receive zero transfer (pool reward doesn't reach the 170 ADA floor, so the 1.5 % margin applies to zero).

**Operator axis — Δ per entity by n-MPO bracket.** Per-pool Δ stacks over the operator's fleet. Each bracket below uses its **mean pools per entity** and **mean pool stake** from the [operator-delegator profitability analysis](../../diagnostic/sub-flows/operator-delegator-distribution/mainnet-analysis/README.md#44-operator-profitability-versus-delegator-return) (epoch 623, retail hollow segment; 73 epochs/yr).

> **Reading aid — the n-MPO axis.** *n* = number of pools the same entity runs. n = 1 means single-pool operator; n ≥ 11 means an entity controlling 11 or more pools. The bracket measures how a reform's revenue impact compounds with fleet size.

| n-MPO bracket | Entities | Pools/entity | Mean stake/pool | $R_{\text{pool}}$ ₳/ep | **Δ per entity per year — standalone** | **Δ per entity per year — paired** |
| --- | ---: | ---: | ---: | ---: | ---: | ---: |
| Single-pool — Sub-reliable (< 3 M) | 155 | 1 | 1.81 M | 564 | **+431 ADA/yr** | **–8 198 ADA/yr** |
| Single-pool — Healthy (3–38.5 M) | 214 | 1 | 11.40 M | 3 554 | +3 706 ADA/yr | –4 920 ADA/yr |
| Single-pool — Large healthy (38.5–62 M) | 29 | 1 | 50.69 M | 15 798 | +17 114 ADA/yr | +8 483 ADA/yr |
| Single-pool — Near-saturation (62–77 M) | 16 | 1 | 69.38 M | 21 623 | +23 491 ADA/yr | +14 863 ADA/yr |
| 2-pool MPO | 17 | 2.00 | 38.24 M | 11 918 | +25 725 ADA/yr | +8 468 ADA/yr |
| 3–5 pool MPO | 24 | 3.92 | 29.47 M | 9 183 | +38 693 ADA/yr | +4 865 ADA/yr |
| 6–10 pool MPO | 9 | 7.44 | 35.37 M | 11 024 | +88 423 ADA/yr | +24 223 ADA/yr |
| 11+ pool MPO | 7 | 19.29 | 33.41 M | 10 413 | **+216 298 ADA/yr** | **+49 852 ADA/yr** |

*Table B.3 — Δ per entity by n-MPO bracket. The 502× gap between the 11+ MPO bracket and the sub-reliable single-pool bracket is the headline.*

> **Finding CIP-0023.S2.F3 [R] — On the operator-fleet axis, the transfer compounds to a 502× gap.** 11+ pool MPO entities gain +216 298 ADA/yr under the standalone variant; sub-reliable single-pool operators gain +431 ADA/yr. The pool-axis 52× amplification and the fleet-axis 9.6× amplification stack multiplicatively — the reform is regressive on the operator layer, mirroring the delegator-layer regressivity it is meant to correct.

> **Finding CIP-0023.S2.F1 [D] — The standalone variant partially flattens the delegator-side fee-rate hyperbola.** Productive-range dispersion compresses from **38× to 13×** — a partial delivery on the CIP's explicit delegator-yield claim. The paired variant (out-of-scope for standalone) reaches 5.5×; CIP-0082 stage 2 reaches 1.00× (see [cip-0082.md](cip-0082.md)).

**Why this fails the missing CPS.** The CPS at [Appendix C.4](#c4-missing-cps-mapping-to-v2-3-1) identifies "the operator growth path is not functioning as intended" as the foundational claim. A reform that (i) fails to materially improve ROS at the small-pool end under its standalone shape, (ii) under its paired shape actively reduces small-operator revenue while raising large-operator revenue, and (iii) in both shapes amplifies the transfer up the MPO ladder via fleet multiplication, is **not a growth-path instrument**. It is a fee-schedule redistribution whose monotonicity on both the pool axis and the operator-fleet axis is the opposite of what the CPS requires.

### B.2. S3 — Below-floor tail untouched

> **Finding CIP-0023.S3.F1 [B] — Below-floor tiers remain 100 % fee-consumed.** Dormant and Sub-block (pools whose epochal reward doesn't reach the 170 ₳ floor) are untouched by today's parameters and by the standalone variant — 100 % of pool reward absorbed by the flat fee. Even the out-of-scope paired variant relieves only Sub-block (100 % → 33 %) and leaves Dormant at 100 %. The instrument does not reach the struggling-pool tail it is nominally meant to help.

### B.3. S1 — Functional redundancy with CIP-0082 stage 2

CIP-0082 stage 2 removes `minPoolCost` and introduces **`minPoolRate`** — mechanically identical to CIP-0023's `minPoolMargin`. The CIP-0082 author explicitly credits CIP-0023 for the concept. CIP-0082 then adds three further stages that reshape the fee layer end-to-end (drop of `minPoolCost`, rate progression, `k` increases), where CIP-0023 stops at the single instrument.

| Scenario | Outcome |
| --- | --- |
| CIP-0023 ships first | Stage 2 of CIP-0082 effectively renames and formalises `minPoolMargin` — `minPoolMargin` becomes a de-facto placeholder for `minPoolRate` |
| CIP-0082 ships first | CIP-0023 is strictly redundant — stage 2 already provides the margin floor, subsequent stages extend it |
| Both enacted as separate items | **Incoherent** — same instrument under two names, governance surface doubled, parameter calibration coupled across two CIPs |

*Table B.4 — How CIP-0023 relates to CIP-0082 stage 2 under three governance scenarios.*

> **Finding CIP-0023.S1.F1 [R] — Same instrument, two governance items.** CIP-0082 stage 2's `minPoolRate` is mechanically identical to CIP-0023's `minPoolMargin`, and the CIP-0082 author credits CIP-0023 explicitly. Ratifying both as separate items doubles the governance surface (two on-chain parameter changes, two calibration decisions, two review cycles) without delivering any additional mechanism — the CIP's core contribution (the margin-floor concept) is preserved intact inside CIP-0082 stage 2.

**Implication.** Treating CIP-0023 and CIP-0082 as independent options forces a false choice — they are not independent. A coherent review cycle picks **CIP-0082** (which contains CIP-0023's instrument) and deprecates CIP-0023 as superseded.

