### C.2. Origin and context

**Authorship and moment.** Written in early-Shelley era, February 2021. The worked example in the CIP uses epoch-382 parameters, with `minPoolCost` at 340 ADA and `a0` at 0.3. The authors' observation: a 100 k ADA delegator faced an effective fee rate of **22.7 %** in a 2 M ADA pool versus **0.7 %** in a saturated 64 M ADA pool — a 32× dispersion driven almost entirely by the fixed cost component. The CIP framed this as a *fairness* problem — delegators penalised for spreading stake across smaller productive pools, and small operators structurally disadvantaged.

**Scope the CIP explicitly excludes.** The text is explicit: *"this proposal does not change or reduce the existing minimum fixed pool fee."* The CIP proposes the margin-floor instrument only. Any reduction in `minPoolCost` is left to a separate governance action. This self-imposed scope restriction is load-bearing for the evaluation — it is why the paired variant in §A.3 and Appendix B.1 is labelled out-of-scope for the standalone CIP.

**Historical placement.** Written before Conway-era governance and before CIP-0082 — whose stage 2 reproduces the margin-floor mechanism under a different name (`minPoolRate`). CIP-0023 is therefore both a live technical proposal and a historical reference point for the margin-floor concept that CIP-0082 later operationalises within a staged path.

### C.3. Diagnostic findings cited

CIP-0023 is a fee-layer instrument acting on the operator/delegator split *after* per-pool allocation. Its rationale attacks two problems at once: the regressive burden on delegators of small productive pools, and the structural disadvantage of the operators running them.

| Finding | Why shared | Supporting observations |
| --- | --- | --- |
| **OPE.O1.F4 — The flat fee follows a $1/\sigma$ hyperbola: 47.5 % of pool reward at the sub-reliable tier, 1.5 % at near-saturation** | The hyperbola is the mechanical consequence of a fixed-in-ADA levy on a size-proportional reward — exactly the regressivity a proportional margin floor rewrites out of the operator take. Maps to the CIP's explicit delegator-yield claim. | OPE.O1.F1 (the flat fee delivers **60 %** of retail operator revenue — the passive channel dominates the active one) · OPE.O5.F1 (sub-reliable delegators pay **18× more** for **0.30 pp** of extra yield — the delegator-side mirror of the hyperbola) |
| **OPE.O6.F1 — A sub-reliable single-pool operator absorbs 48.3 % of pool rewards for 24,820 ADA/yr; an 11+ pool MPO absorbs 7.7 % for 1,035,496 ADA/yr — 42× more revenue at 6× less effective price** | The flat fee penalises small-pool delegators without compensating the operators running those pools. Redirecting take from the fixed channel to a proportional margin floor is the mechanical path toward operator viability at small pool sizes — the CIP's implicit second claim. | OPE.O6.F4 (no single-pool operator in the retail market earns a competitive wage — the ~25,000 ADA/yr median covers infrastructure, not 5–15 hrs/month of skilled labour) |

*Table C.1 — Diagnostic findings the CIP-0023 evaluation depends on.*

### C.4. Missing CPS — mapping to V2 §3.1

CIP-0023 ships without a formal Cardano Problem Statement. Read for what it actually points at, the CIP diagnoses a single mechanical defect: **return-on-stake is structurally unfair between small and large pools for the same delegator**. A delegator placing 100 k ADA in a 2 M pool keeps a far smaller share of that pool's reward than a delegator placing 100 k ADA in a saturated pool — because the flat `minPoolCost` is deducted *before* the margin, so it consumes a disproportionate share of a small pool's reward and only a trivial share of a saturated pool's. The instrument introduced to *ensure operator sustainability at the bottom of the distribution* has inverted its purpose at the delegator layer: it makes small pools **less attractive, not more**.

The reconstructed CPS statement therefore reads:

> **The operator growth path is not functioning as intended.** Small productive pools cannot accumulate the delegation they need to reach viability, because the protocol's own fixed-cost floor — intended to finance their operator — makes them strictly less attractive on net ROS than the large pools they are supposed to grow into. The instrument designed to support the small-pool layer has turned delegator mobility **against** the operators it was meant to protect.

This maps directly onto the foundational V2 specification — [§3.1 Guarantee operator viability across the entire productive population](../../README.md#31-guarantee-operator-viability-across-the-entire-productive-population):

| CPS slot | What V2 §3.1 provides — standing in for CIP-0023's missing CPS |
| --- | --- |
| Problem statement | The mechanism does not guarantee a delegation-mobility path from small productive pools to viable ones. The flat `minPoolCost` is paid out of the pool reward *before* the margin; at small pool sizes it dominates, making those pools uncompetitive on net ROS and stranding their operators below viability |
| Evidence base | OPE.O1.F4 ($1/\sigma$ hyperbola — floor at **47.5 %** of reward in sub-reliable pools vs **1.5 %** at saturation) · OPE.O6.F1 (**42× more revenue at 6× less effective price** — operators who charge most earn least) · OPE.O6.F4 (no single-pool operator earns a competitive wage) |
| Specification | Any instrument that converts the fixed-in-ADA contribution into a size-proportional share, so ROS converges across pool sizes and delegators stop being mechanically steered away from small productive pools |
| Why foundational | V2 §3.1 is declared the **foundational specification** — every downstream problem (delegator yield, concentration, pot sustainability) depends on a functioning growth path. If small pools cannot grow, the productive population hollows out from below |

*Table C.2 — Reconstructed missing-CPS slots filled in by V2 §3.1.*

**Why this is not "just a delegator problem".** The CIP's own rationale is written in delegator-facing language ("remove the regressive effect of `minPoolCost` on delegators"). V2 §3.1 frames it in operator-facing terms (viability, growth path). Both are correct — they are two views of the same asymmetry: the fixed-cost floor couples delegator mobility and operator viability through a single mechanical channel, and fails on both sides simultaneously.

